			<ns0:name>cbiffle@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/cbiffle@google.com/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">We show trybot status on codereview pages like this one: http://codereview.chromium.org/4188006/show

In theory this is a win, except...
1. It's much too wide.  On my 15&amp;quot; laptop I can't even *see* the UI features that I need most -- the &amp;quot;view side-by-side diffs&amp;quot; link and the comments information -- unless I scroll right.
2. The colored indicators we're using assume that the viewer has average color vision.  For people with deuteranopia, there's no alternative indicator of status.  Those with tritanopia will have a hard time distinguishing the &amp;quot;running&amp;quot; yellow from the &amp;quot;broken&amp;quot; red, particularly out of context.  Let's not get started on the more unique variations.
3. It does not appear to be reliable.  I haven't quantified this, but we have a running joke about the &amp;quot;green boxes&amp;quot; that strongly implies the existence of false-negatives.

I suggest that we take out the names and just display small (say 1.5em x 1.5em) boxes.  The background of these boxes could be colored if we want.  Inside the boxes should be a character (ideal) or icon (acceptable) with a legend.  This would fix #1 and #2 above.  I don't understand the system's inner workings well enough yet to propose a solution to #3.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2012-02-23T03:13:52.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2010-10-28T17:24:08.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>Fixed</ns2:status><ns2:cc>
